rText:
When I finally turned on the screen of this television I was disappointed. I'm not sure if it was just my TV but my 5 year old Dynex LED TV had better quality. I tried all different variations in the video settings and found only one setting that didn't make my eyes cringe. So I watched YouTube, Netflix, Amazon Prime Video and played a DVD and Blue Ray through my XBOX and I just couldn't believe that the image wasn't better. I'm a cord-cutter so I didn't check the quality of regular cable or satellite TV.

So I returned this TV and as usual Amazon made it super easy with a UPS pickup. I bought a Vizio 32 inch running at 1080p instead of 720 and I really see the difference. Most people say the difference between a 720 and 1080 on a 32 inch isn't noticeable but to me it is.

The one thing I do have to say about the TCL television is the Roku interface is great. It's way better than the "smart tv" interface of the Vizio I bought. But I'm using my XBOX One to online multimedia access so it's not that big of a deal. The other thing I did appreciate about the TCL is that my Dell XPS 13 laptop was able to mirror display with no cables or setup on my laptop. My laptop was able to recognize my TV and wirelessly use it as a second screen. Unfortunately my Vizio cannot do this :(

pTitle: TCL 55S405 55-Inch 4K Ultra HD Roku Smart LED TV (2017 Model)
rText:
Preface: I'm not a videophile and I have yet to run an 4K sources through the TV.
I wanted to upgrade from my 32" 720p TV and after a few months of window shopping and research, I ended up picking up this TV.

What I like about this TV:
Arrived quickly and undamaged (thanks Amazon Prime)
Lightweight, thin, and great design/finish
Setup was quick and easy/Roku interface works well
Displays/upconverts 1080p sources very well (Amazon streaming/Netflix/Vudu and Blu Ray's)
HDR (a good number of comparable size/priced TV's do not have HDR)

Limitations of the TV:
Viewing angle: I knew that this panel type has a limited viewing angle but for my purposes this doesn't affect me. The image is perfect when TV is directly in front (+/- 15 degrees) of you and more or less eye level. Viewing the TV from a more extreme side angle or above, the image loses detail/gets washed out.

Simulated 120Hz refresh rate: Knew this about the TV as well. It's not jarring or noticeable in slow moving scenes but is there during fast action sequences. The 120Hz cannot be turned off (as far as I know).

Screen glare: In bright rooms, the glare off the screen/bezel can be pretty bad. Obviously, this isn't an issue in darker rooms.

I gave this TV 4 stars because I am reserving 5 stars for higher end TV's. This is really great value for money given that you are getting a brand new 2017 model 49" 4K HDR TV with built in ROKU and simulated 120Hz for the price of a 49" (or smaller) 1080p TV.
rTitle: What I like about this TV

rText:
I bought this for my husband as a Father's Day present and he was blown away. It was in the price range that I could afford and the picture is beautiful. My husband loves to watch videos on You Tube and the Roku setup was very easy. The sound is excellent, better than a Samsung that I bought and returned last year. At this time, I don't have to buy a sound bar like you have to with other TVs. The only complaints I have so far is having to use two remotes. My cable remote does not recognize the TCL codes, so volume control is only with the Roku remote. It's a drag having to use both, but for the price we'll get used to it. The other problem is that side viewing of the picture is weak at best. You really need to be in front of the TV (which makes sense anyway) to view the best picture. The Roku remote is fast and responsive. We're streaming quickly and it did recognize my Spectrum 5G network.

Reading all the reviews, I guess we got lucky that ours was part of a good batch. We love it and feel that we got the best bang for our buck. It's easy to be lured into buying an expensive TV with all the bells and whistles, but this works perfectly and provides us with great picture quality and sound. If you don't mind some of my complaints, then it's a great buy. I purchased it at Costco and got the three year guarantee. If it lasts five years, then I'll get another one at this price.
rTitle: A Fantastic TV for the price range. We Love It!

So far, my issues with the TV is that when showing dark scenes, whether or not it's moving or a still image, becomes pixelated and oddly colored the closer to black it gets. rText:
We purchased this TV for our beach house where we don't have cable and it's been the best addition to our summer home! We've been using Roku (separate box) for a few years now and love that it's integrated directly into the TV, not to mention it's easier to use! No more looking for that second remote and it has my favorite apps -- it's all streamlined and I can watch my favorite shows on demand.
We were concerned the technology was going to be too advanced for us (we're in our 60s), but it took us less than 5 minutes to set up. The picture clarity is fantastic. We've truly noticed a difference with the 4K display.
This TV is the perfect alternative for those who may be considering "cutting the chord" or looking to eliminate another piece of equipment (i.e. Roku box, Apple TV, Google ChromeCast, etc.)

pTitle: TCL 55S405 55-Inch 4K Ultra HD Roku Smart LED TV (2017 Model)
rText: First unit was defective/damaged, as the top middle of the screen wasn't all the way in the frame (bulged out a little) causing lighter spots in that area. Returned and replaced (thanks Amazon). New unit is awesome. I am SHOCKED you can get a 55" 4K TV of this quality for less than $500. way to go TCL!
rTitle: Best TV at This Price Point

pTitle: TCL 55S405 55-Inch 4K Ultra HD Roku Smart LED TV (2017 Model)
rText: This TV goes beyond what I imagined at this price point. I was originally looking at getting the 49" model, but for less than $100, I got this model! Super clear 4K resolution. I previously had an LG (3 years old) and this TCL TV is clearer and crisper.  The built in Roku is also amazing. Easy to use interface, and all the apps I use on my phone are readily accessible on the TV. Loving the fact you can display your laptop monitor on the TV screen.  For me this is huge, because instead of looking at a 20" screen, I can look at a 55" screen. Also, I recently said goodbye to my cable company so I’m excited to explore the updates I’ve been reading about which allows you to record and pause live TV. I get the feeling this will be crucial come football season so I can mind the grill and not miss out on any of the action. I know I need to explore more, and test out the Roku app, but so far extremely happy with this purchase! Might be looking into getting an additional TV for other rooms in the house!

pDescr:
SunBriteTV Veranda is the True Outdoor Television for Full-Shade Applications Like Covered Patios and Screened-In Porches


SunBriteTV Veranda 4K televisions are available in three sizes. This listing is the 43-inch model.
Designed for full-shade applications like a screened-in porch or covered patio, the SunBrite TV Veranda series provides the premium benefits of an true outdoor TV. With a 4K Ultra HD screen that is up to 30% brighter than a typical indoor TV, Veranda brings an incredible picture to outdoor shaded living spaces.  This Veranda model includes built-in speakers, and Veranda protects its components with the same rust-proof aluminum exterior casing and a weatherproof cable entry system found on SunBriteTV's more premium models.

Primary Features
 
Veranda Series – the outdoor TV designed specifically for fully shaded areas like covered patios and screen-in porches
 
Engineered for Outdoor Viewing - the premium 4K Ultra HD high-brightness screen with direct LED backlight is up to 30% brighter than typical indoor televisions
 
Guards Against the Elements – the powder-coated aluminum exterior protects against rust while shielding the internal components from rain, snow, dust, insects, humidity, and salt air
 
Extreme Temperature Functionality - Veranda Series can perform in a temperature range of -24 to 104°F
 
The Veranda Series case offers a large media bay (for streaming media devices) and an innovative weatherproof cable-entry system.

Specifications

Screen: 43-inch Diagonal Color Active Matrix TFT LED
Resolution: 3840 x 2160 UHD
Aspect Ratio: 16:9
Contrast Ratio: 4000:1
VESA Mounting Pattern: 200mm x 200mm
TV Dimensions: 39” x 23.2” x 3.75”
Accessories Included: Weatherproof Remote Control
Speakers: 20 WATT internal speakers
TV Weight: 30 lbs (13.6 kg)

Optional SunBriteTV weatherproof accessories NOT included with television:
Dust cover
TV stand
TV wall mount

This Veranda 4K Series TV is a true outdoor television for fully shaded viewing areas.  For partial-sun and high ambient-light outside installations, the SunBriteTV Signature Series is a great choice.  And for full sun, SunBriteTV recommends its Pro Series.
 
ENGINEERED AND OPTIMIZED FOR OUTDOOR TV VIEWING


Typical Indoor Screens vs. Brighter, Vibrant Outdoor Screens
SunBrite Offers Legendary Outdoor Screens

Most indoor TV screens aren't engineered to perform well in brighter outdoor settings; resulting in in a poor outdoor viewing experience.  The SunBriteTV Veranda series televisions are up to 30% brighter than typical indoor televisions. 

Veranda outdoor televisions feature a premium, 4K UHD high-brightness screen, making them ideal for full-shade areas like a covered patio or screened-in porch. The direct LED backlight delivers an ultra-bright, dramatic picture detail that many indoor TVs can't produce. 
TRUE OUTDOOR TV GUARDS AGAINST THE ELEMENTS


Durable Aluminum Casing Protects Against Weather

Made for permanent outdoor installation, the elements have nothing on the durability of this TV. Outdoor-safe, water resistant, and resilient; the powder-coated aluminum exterior protects against rust while shielding the internal components from rain, snow, dust, insects, humidity, and salt air.


Extreme Temperature Functionality

Built for outdoor weather, the SunBrite Veranda TV series can operate efficiently in extremely low- and high-temperature environments (-24°F up to 104°F).  When not in use, this outside TV can be stored in temperatures ranging from -24°F to 140°F.
 
PROFESSIONAL-GRADE FEATURES FOR IDEAL INSTALLATIONS

		
Built-In Sound

The Veranda series comes with built-in 20W down-firing speakers for an all-in-one sound solution. And, if you want to add an external audio system for even greater punch, it’s easy.
User-Friendly Compatibility

The Veranda series supports HDMI 2.0 and HDCP 2.2 to help ensure compatibility with the latest 4K sources and streaming services, and is equipped with 4 HDMI and 2 USB inputs for various connectivity options. A rear IR receiver located in the cable compartment keeps the IR emitter hidden and protected.
Weatherproof Cable Entry System

Cable hookups are easy with SunBriteTV’s innovative weatherproof cable entry system. Thick gaskets seal out moisture, while the media compartment accommodates most media players, cables, baluns, and extenders.
pTitle: SunBriteTV Outdoor TV 43-Inch Veranda 4K Ultra HD LED Weatherproof Television - SB-4374UHD-BL Black
rText: Perfect size, great picture. This is exactly what we were looking for to put on our deck. We put it on a rolling stand because in this rainy climate though the tv is made for outdoors, we will bring it inside for the winter. Sitting on the deck with a glass of wine watching our favorite program is the best! This tv is highly recommended. The sound is good but my husband is talking about a sound bar. We'll never be inside !!!

Typical Indoor Screens vs. Brighter, Vibrant Outdoor Screens
SunBrite Offers Legendary Outdoor Screens

Veranda outdoor televisions feature a premium, 4K UHD high-brightness screen, making them ideal for full-shade areas like a covered patio or screened-in porch. The direct LED backlight delivers an ultra-bright, dramatic picture detail that many indoor TVs can't produce.

Extreme Temperature Functionality

Built for outdoor weather, the SunBrite Veranda TV series can operate efficiently in extremely low- and high-temperature environments (-24°F up to 104°F).  When not in use, this outside TV can be stored in temperatures ranging from -24°F to 140°F.

Built-In Sound

Weatherproof Cable Entry System

Cable hookups are easy with SunBriteTV’s innovative weatherproof cable entry system. Thick gaskets seal out moisture, while the media compartment accommodates most media players, cables, baluns, and extenders.

pDescr:
Size:19-Inch
Product description
Experience sharp picture quality, even when you are watching fast-moving images like sports or action movies. Clear Motion Rate was developed to accurately measure how well an LCD or LED TV can depict fast-moving images. Previously, motion-clarity was calculated by the frame refresh rate alone. But CMR offers a more complete measure by calculating 3 factors: frame refresh rate, image processor speed and backlight technology. LED TVs with a CMR of 60 -120 can display action-packed movement with sharp detail and vivid contrast while eliminating image distortion. Package Content: DisplayRemoteBatteriesManualWarranty

pTitle: All-New Element 50-Inch 4K Ultra HD Smart LED TV - Amazon Fire TV Edition
rText:
I pre-ordered this TV and it just arrived in the mail yesterday. It does not appear physically damaged, unlike some other reviewers that mentioned this issue. I’m upgrading from a 2014 Vizio Smart TV and it appears quite snappier than that. The look of the TV is very nice and modern as well. Sound and picture quality is very good compared to my previous TV. Apps also download very fast directly on the TV, loading and scrolling much quicker than the same apps I’ve downloaded on my Xbox One. The stand was easy to install and seems to be fairly sturdy.

The main reason I purchased this TV is because of the voice control attraction. I’m a big fan of the Kinect 2.0 on my Xbox one, and Microsoft doesn’t seem to be upgrading it as they release new consoles. I was able to turn the TV on, off, switch channels, apps, volume, etc using the Xbox and wanted to unify this technology through the purchase of this Amazon TV because it lets you voice navigate through different inputs rather than just one input like on the Xbox.

Although voice command works very well on this TV, I knew that it still requires you to press a button when speaking into the remote. Hence, I cannot turn the TV on and off simply by my voice, which means I still need to have the remote in my hands rather than be hands-free like the Xbox Kinect. I also cannot use my voice to change channels if using a cable box plugged into the TV, it seems this will only work when using it for over-the-air channels with an optional antenna.

Overall, the inability to change channels via the voice remote if watching live TV on my cable box is disappointing. I have to use the cable TV remote or a universal remote, in both cases I will have to switch between that standard remote and my Amazon voice remote. I was hoping for a unified experience where the Amazon TV remote could be used for everything, since the Xbox is able to do this already. I gain the ability to switch inputs by voice (while holding the mic button) on Amazon TV, but lose the ability to control my cable box’s live channels.

I’m currently on the fence if I should keep or return this TV for the above reasons. It is faster with upgraded picture quality, but it is not a seamless experience that I was expecting. If we need to operate multiple remotes, it might have just been cooler we can talk straight at the TV without the remote for everything and that way would only need to use a remote for the cable box channels. Then again, I am wondering how Xbox is able to let me switch cable box channels by voice in more than 4-year old technology and this TV still cannot…
rTitle: Can't change Cable TV channels by Voice

pTitle: All-New Element 50-Inch 4K Ultra HD Smart LED TV - Amazon Fire TV Edition
rText:
Decided to give this a try over the TCL/Roku model because it looked it would be better for antenna tv (built in guide, DVR, etc.). So far, the user experience has been poor and the software seems buggy.

- I can find no way to rescan for over-the-air channels after the initial scan. If your antenna wasn't positioned right, your only option (as far as I can tell) is to reset the TV back to factory defaults.
- I tried to download the WatchESPN app and kept getting a message 'WatchESPN for Fire TV is incompatible with your Device' (see photo)
- Interface is very busy. Maybe I'll get used to it but for now I prefer the Apple TV / Roku interfaces that are cleaner and make it easier to find specific apps.

I'm sure Amazon will improve the software but for now this needs work. I'll give it a try for a few more days but it may be headed back..

pTitle: All-New Element 50-Inch 4K Ultra HD Smart LED TV - Amazon Fire TV Edition
rText:
Unlike speakers and laptops, I don’t purchase a lot of new televisions. I didn’t get a HD set until my Trinitron wouldn’t power on and I didn’t get a big screen LCD until I upgraded to a Blue-Ray DVD player. I had no intention of getting a 4K set until broadcast channels bragged about it, and I didn’t care if it was a “smart TV” or not because television manufactures abandon those sets a year or two after they sell them. Whatever 4K set I would own, it would get all its “smarts” from the latest edition of the Fire TV box. When I saw Element was integrating Fire TV into a 4K set, I was interested. (I have been secretly waiting for the Fire TV boxes got get an integrated tuner, this is the next best thing.)
Setup was straightforward. After attaching the feet, you plug it in, push the power button and it starts up. The first boot gives you a tutorial and run-through of the interface. You can find them again under the Notifications Bell if you skip it. The boot time is a little long since you must wait for both the Element logo and the normal Fire TV startup process. After the first startup, it gets quicker.
If are familiar with the Fire TV, you will be right at home, but I am glad I did not ignore the tutorial, without it, I would not have found how to scan for channels with my antenna. You find the antenna input, then push the menu button to find the Scan Channels option.
After scanning for channels, I had one issue. The sound was horrible. I scanned for channels again, checked the settings on my Yamaha receiver, and tried again. It was still terrible, like there was static, or the television speaker was on with the receiver and I was getting an echo from the interference. I moved my mud-flap antenna and tried scanning channels again with the same result. I played around in the TV’s settings and found I had a software update waiting. The update fixed the sound issue.
That’s another reason I like Amazon’s Fire TV ecosystem. Even my first generation Fire TV is running current software. I hope this set gets the same service. (OK better service, since I intend to keep the set longer than a $40 Fire TV box).
I have been cable television free for four years. When Amazon announced the “channels” option for Amazon Video I knew it was the ecosystem for me. If you have not used the add-on channels feature of Amazon Video, you should, it’s as close to à la carte cable television as you can get. Add Netflix and you will not miss cable television. Add the integrated antenna TV guide and you have a complete package. It is so nice that I might spring for that outdoor antenna to clear up some weak channels my indoor mud-flap antenna cannot pick up (antenna TV is a long way from the four channels I had as a child). When you are in the guide, you can hit the menu button to add channels to a favorite list and filter out all the clutter, that should be enough to keep from a new antenna. A feature I did not expect is that the “live” channels of my HBO add-on channel are included in the guide. My favorite channel list is now the HBO channels, ABC, CBS, CW, FOX, NBC, and the three PBS stations. (OK, and the Accu-Weather channel. I am guilty).
When you hold down the Home button, you get a fly-out menu that gets you into the Channel Guide, where you can select inputs, your applications, the sleep timer and your picture and sound settings. Since I use a Yamaha receiver and Polk speakers, I can’t speak for the sound options. The options for adjusting the picture are limited to the usual presets and some advanced options. Before you spend a lot of time tweaking these, know that you will have to do so at least twice. Once for live TV, and again for Video. Since you are not switching inputs, this frustrated me, until I found the mode indicator at the top of the Picture Settings menu. You can tweak your settings for each mode, and that is a good thing.
You Advanced Options are limited to Motion Smoothing, Noise Reduction, Color Temperature and Color Mode. If you want finer control, then you must start with the Custom Picture Mode setting to gain access to Brightness, Contrast, Saturation, Tint, and Sharpness. If you are looking for finer adjustments, you are out of luck.
For now, I have chosen the Standard picture mode, turned noise reduction and motion smoothing to their lowest settings, set the color mode to native, and chose the standard color temperature. The set comes with all these on their highest settings or auto along with the backlight at an eye-searing 100. I am playing with the backlight between off and very low (below 25) with nice results.
The remote is the standard Fire TV remote affair, except the home, reverse, and menu buttons are above the ring (annoying). The prime video, Netflix, and Amazon Music buttons are a nice touch, and thanks to HDMI CEC control I retired my smart remote. Powering the set on, powers up my Yamaha receiver and the volume buttons pass through to my receiver as well.
Overall, I am happy with the set. Since cutting the cable cord, the number of devices on my television stand have been dwindling, and that makes me very happy. Now if a set would just come with some really rocking speakers, you know like the consoles of old…
rTitle: The Almost Perfect Cord Cutting Dream

pTitle: All-New Element 50-Inch 4K Ultra HD Smart LED TV - Amazon Fire TV Edition
rText:
When I found out the price of this TV, I was pleasantly surprised. Basically, I got 4K TV with smart features for the price of a Full HD one. At first sight, this TV seems like worthy competitors to budget Roku TVs by brands like TCL.

It's a bit thicker than I expected. Honestly saying it is really thick, almost as thick as my old LG TV which I bought in 2010 on Black Friday. Don't build false expectation about this Element, it looks like upgraded version of some old TV with a 4K panel which actually doesn't look as good as, for example, Samsung or LG 4K panels.
But it has a solid mix of ports (four HDMI, USB 2.0, USB 3.0, Ethernet, VGA, RCA inputs, and SD card slot) - more than enough for me and, probably, for most people on this planet. But actually, what differs this 4K TV among others is Amazon's Fire and Alexa built in it. And that is really cool, as I can use voice commands to control my TV now (and all those people whose TV remote disappears from time to time). Actually, if you have this TV, you don't need to buy this new Echo Show thing, which I think is a bit overpriced. As I have this TV now, I can tell Alexa to turn on my smart thermostat etc. I can also use voice to search for TV shows and movies, launch apps, fast-forward and pause in supported apps.

Just a small remark, in devices like Echo dot or Echo show, I can talk "into the air", just as long as Alexa can hear me. But with this TV, I have to press the audio button on TV remote and then talk into the remote control, like into the microphone. It doesn't bother me, but consider this before buying.

The picture quality is good, it is not perfect and not even close to OLED panels, but do not forget about the price. Also, there is no HDR or local dimming. Maybe it still doesn't have this "wow" effect like OLED TV has, but the picture looks OK. I noticed that saturation is a bit higher than I would expect but I can deal with it.

The main difference between this TV and a TV with a fire stick is that the last one can't pull in streams from PS, Xbox or your antenna. But Fire TV detects the devices I've connected to my TV and display them in a "content row". As well, I can manage live content: rewind it 90 seconds back, if I think I missed something.

CONCLUSION:
If you are on a limited budget, and "value" of the device is more important than a fancy look; if you have the craving for a smart 4K TV - this is your choice. The picture is good, and the interface is well designed and easy to use. Looking at the same features in LG or Samsung, I would have to pay much more. In both basic functionality and advanced features, this TV is a winner. In general, I am satisfied with the quality and price.
rTitle: It still doesn't have this "wow" effect like OLED TV has, but the picture looks OK

rText:
This is a first impression. I am satisfied with the tv quality itself. I am coming from a 4 year old Samsung so the picture looks good compared to what I had. However, I am unhappy with the integration of the over the air channels. I cannot find a way to delete channels I do not want, which is about half of them. This leaves me scrolling endlessly through the guide trying to look at what's on tv. I also wish the guide was in order of channel number and not alphabetical order. I guess I misjudged the description of integration of over the air and streaming channels, such as Sling. I assumed it would more along the lines of both types of channels being integrated into one guide. I don't really feel like I gained anything buying this as a tv versus just buying the amazon streaming device and connecting it to any other tv.
<Edit 07/5/17> Antenna channel surfing is much easier after following helpful suggestion to set wanted channels as favorites and then choose option to only show favorites. That is enough for me to change it to four stars.

pTitle: Samsung Electronics UN40MU7000 40-Inch 4K Ultra HD Smart LED TV (2017 Model)
rText:
We took delivery of this TV May 17, 2017. I will focus my review on 4 aspects:

1) Set-up: If you have a degree in advanced electronics the set-up is probably quite easy, despite the less-than-transparent remote that comes with the set, but since I am technologically challenged the process was very frustrating. Daily use of the remote has not become any less frustrating .

2) Picture quality: excellent

3) Sound quality: Mixed message. The sound is fine, but there are regular and increasing audio dropouts (very brief, but very annoying). This happens not only with TV broadcasts but also the dvd player, and we are told by Spectrum that this means the problem is with the set, not their service. We have not yet been able to receive an answer from Samsung about the problem.

4) I expect more from a $1500 purchase and will be returning this item unless the problem can be resolved.

rText: I bought this set to replace a Samsung series 6400 that failed after only about 30 months. When I got this, I was stunned by the picture quality. But about two weeks later I put on some 4K programming. All of a sudden there was an apparent "gray shadow" over the left quarter of the screen. It was about a foot wide and ran top to bottom of the picture. It was in every scene of all programming. I've contacted Amazon and they are having this one picked up and I'm exchanging this for an 8000 series. If the 8000 fails in under four years, I will never have another Samsung in my house. I have bought five Samsungs and only one is still operational. Despite being highly rated by testing labs, I have not had good luck with the Samsung brand.

pTitle: Samsung Electronics UN55J6201AFXZA 54.6" 1080p Smart LED TV
rText:
So first off, I bought this locally at a member warehouse store, where today 3/5/17 it is $80 cheaper including a free 2nd year warranty, so keep that in mind. They will ship free as well BTW, though admittedly not Prime fast. So why write the review here, so someone else doesn't make my "sort of" mistake. Had a 2016 65" Sharp Aquos 1080p, moved, didn't fit well, needed to downsize, friend broke their 65", so took the opportunity to sell it to them. I specifically needed this sort of rectangular flat stand to fit the space, not 3 point foot like the Samsung 4k, or 2 separate feet. Really bought this just for the stand configuration, and to interface (I thought) seamlessly with a Samsung soundbar I already had for the Sharp. Aside for the PS4 Plus, no need for 4k. Bought this specifically as I had that Samsung soundbar, expected this 6 series unit to work with Soundshare Bluetooth. Didn't say it would but the box (and manual) are totally bereft of Specifications so didn't say it wouldn't. It doesn't, no Bluetooth, interfaces no better than the Sharp did. Didn't pay attention (again no specs, just a picture) that it only has 2 HDMI ports, really 2016 model HD TV with only 2 HDMI ports?? And those ports stick straight out, not down, glad I couldn't wall hang it, would be buying right angle HDMIs, well only 2 at least...

Anyway makes it so Amazon at least does get the $11 for a HDMI switch from me to use the PS4 and Blueray without swapping cables.

As noted the Smart features are limited and slower, but streams Netflix fine which is all I care.

Display is strong point, crystal clear, nice blacks, exceptional fast motion capabilities. Sound even without the soundbar is very good for a flatpanel, way better than the Sharp. Some interface annoyances, like a pain just to change picture size/zoom you got to delve through menus. Cosmetically the screen surround is bright, looks cheesey, reflects room lights.

All in all, just an OK TV for when it was released in late 2015 as a 2016 model, pretty sad, even for a 1080p by spring 2017 standards. But fit where and how I needed it to. One would do far better price wise with a newer 1080p model by another manufacturer and could even touch a 4k for this price going off brand.
rTitle: Just an OK set by 2017 standards.

pDescr: The UJ657A elevates your HDR experience even higher with Active HDR, which optimizes content scene-by-scene for an more precise, lifelike picture. Active HDR also has the broadest compatibility, supporting the most content choices from streaming and disc, plus backward-compatible HLG. The IPS panel in LG TV uses in-plane switching to deliver rich colors and a strong contrast ratio that remain consistent at wide viewing angles. With IPS 4K, any seat becomes the best in the house.
pTitle: LG 75" 4K UHD HDR Smart LED TV - 75UJ657A
rText:
Review of LG 75UJ657A LED TV

A big reason I chose this TV because the web interface is the most advanced out there (in my opinion). Additionally the remote is user friendly with great choice of quick options (again my opinion). My last TV was a 60” “E” series 2012 model and the Yahoo web interface was just awful and as a result we never used the web interface. Additionally I am not a TV guru, but rather an average viewer with some common sense of what works and what doesn't. With that said, on to the review...

Out of the box the LG 75UJ657A does not present the best picture it is capable of. The LG requires “tweaking” to achieve that and by best picture I mean the best for each individual viewer. After “playing” with all the adjustments I can say there are many ways to adjust the picture to most anyone's preference. Following are the settings I used to achieve my “LG nirvana.” Yours will vary. There are several preset picture modes such as Standard – Sports – Vivid – Cinema – Game, etc. With these you can tweak one for your liking and for example your wife can tweak another for hers. Therefor you both have your preferences saved. To change just choose the setting button on the remote and then it's the 2nd from top option on the right side of the screen. Easy!

PICTURE MODE: - On remote press SETTINGS – Then right side menu, 2nd from top choice.
Set to (Standard) - Game is a close second.
Note: When you pick a Picture Mode; to make additional adjustments (listed below) to that mode, go the the more advanced settings menu on the left side of the screen. You get there by pressing the SETTINGS button on the remote which brings up a set of menu buttons on the right side of the screen. You then go to the last one on the bottom (ALL SETTINGS) to get to ALL SETTINGS. The menu on the right side is for quick settings like choosing your picture mode. After choosing ALL SETTINGS, the left menu will come up with PICTURE on top.

The setting I chose in the menu on the LEFT.
PICTURE:
ASPECT RATIO – (Original)
EYE COMFORT MODE – (off)
ENERGY SAVINGS – (off)
-----Now Choose PICTURE MODE SETTINGS.

PICTURE MODE SETTINGS:
BACKLIGHT – (86)
CONTRAST – (70)
BRIGHTNESS - (69)
SHARPNESS – (18)
COLOR – (60)
-----Now choose ADVANCED CONTROLS.

ADVANCED CONTROLS:
DYNAMIC CONTRAST – (low)
DYMAMIC COLOR – (med)
COLOR GAMUT – (auto)
SUPER RESOLUTION – (med)
GAMMA – (med)

By no means did I cover all the settings, but rather just the adjustments I made from default settings. Your preferences will be different I'm sure, but this is a good starting point.

Additional item: Update the Software. Mine came with 03.50.40 / the new update is 03.60.03 as of 6/21/2017.

Overall I am happy with the LG. High marks for me are...
Web OS is the best out there. That makes a big difference.
Remote is more functional than others.
Great value in cost comparison versus other 2017 models.
Large variety of picture adjustments.
Great adjustments for sound too.

The cons are: There are people out that just don't want to spend the time tweaking this TV so they might be better buying a Samsung. I don't recommend Vizio because My 60” “E” series had to be completely replaced, then two years later both circuit boards were replaced. Thankfully I had an extended warranty.
rTitle: Additionally the remote is user friendly with great choice of quick options (again my opinion)

pDescr:

pTitle: LG Electronics 28LJ4540 28-Inch 720p LED TV (2017 Model)
rText: This 28" LG is an exceptional smaller-sized LED flat screen TV. It has a remarkably sharp picture with very natural color and many options for customizing the picture and sound. It's a good choice for placing in an entertainment center in a small room, which is how we're using ours. The only drawback I've found is that this particular model has only one HDMI port for connecting accessories. I had to buy an HDMI adapter unit with additional ports in order to hook-up both the HD TV cable and a DVD/Blu-Ray player. Other than that, the TV is great and was a real bargain for the $179.00 asking price.

Thanks to HEVC decoding and ultra-fast 802.11ac dual-band Wi-Fi (up to 3x faster¹), you’ll get Ultra HD streaming from popular apps like Netflix, Amazon Instant Video and UltraFlix². It all adds up to a beautifully simple experience where the picture is everything and nothing is more captivating!

pTitle: VIZIO D55u-D1 55" Class Ultra HD Full-Array LED Smart TV (Black)
rText:
I've had this 4k TV for 7 months now.
I love love love love it!!!!

The 4k is still not mainstream really, but the future proofing is nice.
I watch some shows from Amazon Prime through the Built-in app and the 4k is lovely.
My 1gb/s internet handles the stream no problem.
Is 4k super obviously noticeable over 1080p? Not really.
The crispness and little details are there but the eye doesn't really care....

The price is phenomenal on this TV. Even back when I got it for $800 it was a steal IMHO.

I got it from B.Buy so they tried to talk me out of it, and into a Sony for $1200.
I didn't really care what they said and dismissed them. I'm glad I did.
This TV is great. The picture is wonderful. It has plenty of inputs.
The Sound I don't use since I have a 5.1 surround system but I imagine it works as any small internal sound system would. which is poorly lol.
I've tried it a few times and it's good enough for hearing sounds lol. But it won't blow you away of course.

I'm going to be purchasing a home soon and I think a few more of these TV's may be in my future.

pTitle: VIZIO D55u-D1 55" Class Ultra HD Full-Array LED Smart TV (Black)
rText:
*I did not buy this TV from Amazon. I got a great deal from Target last week. This review will be fore the TV itself only.*

This tv really is a great value for the price. It is not high end like $2k Sony or Samsung, but for $500 the quality is superb.
Pros: Quality for gaming is awesome
Sound is decent
Plays 1080p if content is 1080p
5 HDMI ports!
WiFi & Ethernet connections
Build in Apps (some are meh..)
You can cast some apps from your phone/tablet directly to this TV (like Chromecast)

Cons: Back panel for 3 HDMI ports are a bit pain in the rear to reach and connect.
Some build-In apps are outdated or non popular
Some lower resolution contents seems worst than my older TV.

Overall I like what this TV offers for $550 I paid. I am not a TV techie, just a regular Joe who enjoys playing game and watching movies casually. I do can tell a decent quality TV or not.

pDescr:
Product Description
Introducing the all-new VIZIO D-series Ultra HD Full-Array LED Smart TV. With over 8.3 million pixels in every image, four times the resolution of 1080p Full HD, D-series Ultra HD displays produce breathtaking detail and clarity. Full-Array LED backlighting and 14 Active LED Zones deliver superior light uniformity with an extremely high contrast, and deep, pure black levels. Active Pixel Tuning enables pixel-level brightness adjustments for increased picture accuracy and contrast. And with Clear Action 240, sports and action fans will appreciate the powerful image processing of the D-series with a blazing 120Hz effective refresh rate achieved with backlight scanning for sharper detail in fast action scenes. In addition, the beautifully designed D-series is optimized to deliver all of your favorite entertainment in stunning 4k Ultra HD right out of the box. Thanks to HEVC decoding and ultra-fast 802.11ac dual-band Wi-Fi (up to 3x faster¹), you’ll get Ultra HD streaming from popular apps like Netflix, Amazon Instant Video and UltraFlix². Its powerful Spatial Scaling Engine beautifully transforms your favorite 720p and 1080p HD sports, movies, and TV shows into near Ultra HD. And support for the latest HDMI standards enables Ultra HD playback from next generation cable and satellite receivers, Blu-ray players and game consoles. It all adds up to a beautifully simple experience where the picture is everything and nothing is more captivating!

pTitle: VIZIO D55u-D1 55" Class Ultra HD Full-Array LED Smart TV (Black)
rText:
Gaming, movies and editing!

I recently bought this to get buying a tv for my next apartment out of the way. I'm moving in May so I'm slowly buying all new furniture. I just built a pc and sadly the new graphics card won't hook up to my ancient monitor without a HDMI to VGA converter. So as soon as I got the tv from Target I decided to hook up my computer to it. I did tons of test to make sure the tv was a good purchase. I played 4k content and was immediately happy. I then played games to see if I would encounter the infsmous ghosting and or screen tearing. Everything was perfect. Battlefield 1 looked ridiculously good running at 4k. I'm a photographer and I really didn't want to boot up my older pc and edit my new batch of photos. So I tried on this massive screen. The color was dead on. Meaning I could edit my photos and not worry about it looking different when it came time for prints or social media uploading. So in conclusion this tv seems to be far better than expected on such a cheap display. I highly recommend it! I hope I answered some people's concerns on buying it. The speakers are very good as well. In fact I have yet to hook up my other speakers.
rTitle: Gaming, movies and even a pc monitor!?

pTitle: Samsung UN43KU7500 Curved 43-Inch 4K Ultra HD Smart LED TV (2016 Model)
rText:
Do not buy this TV if you want good HDR support. This TV only supports one HDR input (HDMI1). The other inputs do not support HDR video, so if you have an XBox One S and a Playstation 4, you'll have to choose which one gets to be HDR, because it can't be both.

Unfortunately, this limitation is not revealed in the specs or anywhere else, but can be found in the on-screen e-manual built into the TV.

Because of this limitation, I can't recommend this TV, as it will not serve the ongoing and future needs of anyone who wants HDR content from more than one source.
rTitle: Serious HDR input limitations. Avoid this TV

rText: I bought mine in December 2016 from Best Buy not Amazon, even though I am a Prime member. I paid about $1,300. I was very happy with the TV until last week when the picture went bad with a big three inch Shadow from top to bottom of screen! Lucky for me it is under manufacturer's warranty. Had this happened 5 or 6 months from now it would have been cheaper just to buy a new TV because the part alone is $800! My local service company that Samsung is using for warranty repair says there is absolutely no quality control anymore with new televisions and recommends buying the warranty. I used to think warranties were for suckers but with the cheap quality control I'm changing my tune!

pTitle: Samsung UN55KS800DFXZA 55" 4K 240 MR LED SMART TV (Certified Refurbished)
rText: First let me state that I did not purchase my Tv from Amazon. I went through Samsung. This tv seemed amazing at first. Design seemed to be of the highest quality and probably is on a whole. The unit I have started developing issues that are far more common that you would think. Within the first two or three months pixels died in three different spots, shortly after that I started to see what I can only say was color separation similar to what you'd see looking at an old 3D image. The separation/blurring slowly became worse, now it happens numerous times daily. If you do your research you'll see that many people have reported this type of issue, many times though it is also related to Xbox users. Make no mistake this is primarily a Samsung issue. I'd have given a slightly better review but Samsung hasn't been very cooperative in repairing or replacing the unit. If you don't live in a populated city I urge caution as you may end up getting the short end of the stick should you require service.
rTitle: Great tv but... you'll be rolling the dice.

pTitle: Samsung UN55KS800DFXZA 55" 4K 240 MR LED SMART TV (Certified Refurbished)
rText:
Beautiful piece of hardware. Totally worth whatever you have paid for it. I will not discuss its pros, there are too many. Go to a bestbuy and see yourself.
But it has several small issues that are somewhat annoying. One is its buggy WIFI module. Sometimes my Netflix and YouTube just stop working and I need to unplug tv to reset it to working condition.

Second issue, at some point Samsung pushed Ads through TV's OS. I was very unhappy about it. It is a premium product, there should be 0 ads, Samsung.0 ads!

Other thoughts: After careful research, I am happy I didn't follow the hype and didn't buy a curved model. It looks absolutely ugly on the wall, and offers no advantage unless it is 65+ inch. Don't buy curved, people. It is more expensive and absolutely not worth extra.
Also, I agree with R-tings regarding this model being best in many categories. People who made this panel did an outstanding job. And while Vizio's and LG's models offer similar quality, they either fall short in design or price compared to this model.

pTitle: Samsung UN55KS800DFXZA 55" 4K 240 MR LED SMART TV (Certified Refurbished)
rText:
Bottom line is if you want to use the apps/wireless connection so that YouTube, Netflix, etc. works, don't get this TV because the wireless cards and/or software is so poor that the wifi doesn't work. Don't take my word for it, go online and read the product forums and see how many people are complaining about this model and wireless issues, it's insane that a TV this expensive can't maintain a wireless connection when a Chromcast can. The 2017 model has gotten even worse reviews.

I'm a fan of Samsung's other products (phone and tablet) so I ordered two of these TVs for our home, and in both TVs, the wireless doesn't work. It'll last 10 minutes then disconnect, requiring a restart of the TV to reconnect. The wireless router is within 50 feet and shows a strong signal and all other devices work perfectly on the same wireless network. I read all the online forums, tried everything recommended (DNS settings, factory reset, modem reset, called Comcast and Samsung support) and nothing worked, even Samsung said it's a faulty wireless card.

On the plus side, the picture itself is fantastic, the user interface is great and the remote is sleek and works well too, and the TV design looks great. This is why I gave 2 stars and not 1. This TV works well if you know you're going to use a Roku, Chromecast or game console to access streaming apps anyway and aren't going to use the TV's own wireless connection.

I returned both of these and I'm getting an LG instead, you should avoid these TVs from Samsung.
rTitle: Don't Buy if you Plan to Use Wireless, Otherwise Great TV

pTitle: Samsung UN55KS800DFXZA 55" 4K 240 MR LED SMART TV (Certified Refurbished)
rText: TV had back panel separation out of the box and serious light bleed. The TV was put on a stand with a mount when i purchased it in November 2016 and hasn't been moved since. On May 25th, 2017 I turned the tv on and went to another room, when i came back the screen had parallel lines going across the entire screen and looked like it shattered inside. I contacted Samsung right away and on June 6th the "technician" came and all he did was take pictures of the front of the TV when its on. He did not take pictures of it when its off or of the back panel separating. The following day I contacted Samsung and they informed me that the warranty is void and claimed physical damage. Nothing hit this tv, it never fell, it was always hanging on the stand since November. The screen has not even a scratch on it. I went on the Consumer Affairs website and found multiple people with the same issue and for them too Samsung claimed physical damage and refused to do anything about it. Samsung also refused to acknowledge the back panel issue even though on their forums there multiple pages of people with this issue and even the so called technician told me that during manufacturing they used 3M adhesive to secure the back panel which isn't secure enough and separates. I contacted office of the president for Samsung and they blamed BestBuy where I purchased the tv for back panel separation. Thats absurd! Samsung has a terrible reputation for quality control(Note 7, washers, etc.) and I will never purchase another Samsung product again and would suggest other do the same. Stay away from Samsung.

pTitle: Samsung UN55KS800DFXZA 55" 4K 240 MR LED SMART TV (Certified Refurbished)
rText: If you are using the television speakers and you adjust the picture to specifications in a cnet.com article, I would rate the TV 5 stars. (The picture without the cnet adjustments was terribly disappointing with cartoon-like colors.) However if you want your sound to be passed through an A/V receiver (Marantz in my case), it is very difficult using the Samsung mandatory one connect box (OCB). The OCB has not been thought-out by Samsung with A/V receivers in mind. You can patch something together with on-line help from a number of blogs that provide much conflicting information, but it is not elegant nor satisfactory for all possible A/V receiver HDMI connections. Samsung's website is not much help. My 3 star rating is an average, as my rating for my case is 2 stars. Look elsewhere is you want less frustration in your life.
